<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1902-01-03T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1902-01-03T00:00:00-05:00" n="349" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d349">
                        <head><hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Hay</persName> to Mr.
                                    <persName type="to">Cambon</persName></hi>.</head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1902-01-03"><hi rend="italic">January 3,
                                1902</hi></date>.</dateline>
                            <seg rendition="#left">No. 439.]</seg></opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Excellency</hi>: I have the honor to acknowledge the
                            receipt of Mr. de Margerie’s note of the 22d ultimo, relating further to
                            the violation of the consular convention of February 23, 1853, by
                            officials of the United States and the States, in the ports on the
                            Pacific coast, and to inform you in reply that I have sent copies of it
                            to the Attorney-General, the Secretary of the Treasury, and the
                            governors of California and Oregon for their information and
                            consideration.</p>
                        <p>Accept, etc.,</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">John Hay</hi>.</signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>